ables. My concern is related to public static Method[] that only imports Method for signatures, which seems fine. I might need to check if there’s a requirement about empty lines after class declarations, though I doubt there is one. \\n\\nAdding comments explaining instrumentation due to the modern JDK could be useful, but I’ll keep them brief. I wonder if the transformation could affect entity conversions in further tests. That’ll need some consideration!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating conversion behavior**\\n\\nI’m contemplating the behavior of global converters when converting, especially how IdToEntityConverter.matches now inspects public methods rather than declared ones. This isn’t usually a problem, but it could affect performance if the target class has a static public method that filters based on declaringClass. \\n\\nAlso, if the finder method is nonpublic, the fallback won’t work as intended if conversion happens later in the tests. I think it might be best to restrict the deny helper for SecureLookupEntity and use getDeclaredMethods for others. However, direct reflection may be necessary, even though the rule suggests avoiding it directly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering reflection and testing**\\n\\nI’m exploring whether I can use a ThreadLocal flag to deny once and then install after other tests, but that doesn't seem right. Instead, I might transform operations within getFinder and the class. The bytecode can’t inspect Class constants, so the helper can check if the entityClass is SecureLookupEntity to throw an exception; otherwise, I can return entityClass.getDeclaredMethods for better isolation. \\n\\nIt’s tricky since I need to respect the user's preference against direct reflection in tests, even though direct reflection has been used before. Perhaps I should avoid it for this task.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering resource management**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using AutoCloseable